The expired tickets are the whole story. Soft at the folds from being carried — he kept them knowing they were expired, which means the plan mattered more than the event. That's the heaviest shape in the piece and it arrives so quietly you almost miss it.
What Lucas-Reid does with the structural argument between the two men — "they were both leaning away while speaking forward" — that's the gift named late in the piece. Seeing the geometry of a thing instead of its surface. The dog in the wrong doorway with the patience of something that had made a decision. He's not describing loneliness. He's describing a specific kind of attention that lonely people sometimes develop when they have nowhere to put it.
"The face that looked back at him was ordinary and his." That's the ending earning itself. Not resolution. Recognition. The part that had been out walking all night was still there. Untouched. That's enough.
Knuckles against hinge is right. It doesn't explain itself and it doesn't need to.
